The `/etc/group` file lists all of the groups on the system.
We can then use the [getent](https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/getent.1.html) command to list members of any interesting groups.
```shell-session
GANGADHAR565@htb[/htb]$ getent group sudo
```

#### User's Last Login
It can also be helpful to check out each user's last login time to try to see when users typically log in to the system and how frequently. This can give us an idea of how widely used this system is which can open up the potential for more misconfigurations or "messy" directories or command histories.
```shell-session
 lastlog
```

#### Finding History Files
```shell-session
find / -type f \( -name *_hist -o -name *_history \) -exec ls -l {} \; 2>/dev/null
```

### Cron jobs
Cron jobs on Linux systems are similar to Windows scheduled tasks. They are often set up to perform maintenance and backup tasks. In conjunction with other misconfigurations such as relative paths or weak permissions, they can leverage to escalate privileges when the scheduled cron job runs
```shell-session
 ls -la /etc/cron.daily/
```

### Proc
The [proc filesystem](https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/proc.5.html) (`proc` / `procfs`) is a particular filesystem in Linux that contains information about system processes, hardware, and other system information. It is the primary way to access process information and can be used to view and modify kernel settings
```shell-session
find /proc -name cmdline -exec cat {} \; 2>/dev/null | tr " " "\n"
```

